ng of modernist priorities and demonstrates how readily these ideas translate across genres. It shows that modernists are not passive recipients of baroque stereotypes but are instead painstaking in their research and innovative in their reworking of original sources. This is an introduction to key ideas, characters and techniques that will allow the baroque to be used as a conceptual and historical framework for analysing modernist achievements, thereby opening up new opportunities for further research.Key featuresFashions an independent aesthetic for modernist writers and texts that challenges many high modernist qualities promoted by James Joyce and T. S. EliotProvides new connections between philosophy/critical theory and modernist culture, links that are relevant to both popular and academic interestIntroduces key ideas, characters and techniques that allow the baroque to be used as both a conceptual and historical framework for analysing modernist achievements, thereby opening up new opportunities for research, and demonstrating how readily these ideas translate across genre  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aAesthetics, BaroquexInfluence. 0aBaroque literaturexInfluence. 0aBaroque literature. 0aEnglish literaturey20th centuryxBaroque influences. 0aEnglish literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aModernism (Art). 0aTheaterxPolitical aspectszEuropexHistory. 0aTheaterzEuropexHistory. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311078140340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781474419635?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474419635423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474419635/original  a978-3-11-078140-3  Edi